{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472865"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1561"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1561"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.51,0.18,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94262"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77327"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"831"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12730"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42342"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94262"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old Indigenous boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of an itchy scalp. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Examination of his scalp reveals live eggs and nits located 5mm from the scalp (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wet combing with conditioner daily","Permethrin 1% lotion, repeat in 7 days","Dimeticone 4% gel, repeat in 7 days","Total head shave","Oral ivermectin, repeat in 7 days"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has head lice (\u003Cem\u003EPediculus humanus capitis\u003C/em\u003E). Head lice are a common problem, and outbreaks can occur in schools or community groups. The location of nits relative to the scalp is diagnostically important - as hair grows at approximately 1cm per month, nits found more than 6mm from the scalp indicate old, inactive infection, while those within 6mm suggest current infection. Live eggs can be distinguished from empty nit cases as they make an audible \u0022pop\u0022 when crushed between fingernails.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDimeticone 4% gel\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective first-line treatment that works by physically blocking the respiratory system of the lice, causing asphyxiation. It has several advantages over traditional insecticides: it is non-toxic, does not rely on chemical activity (so resistance cannot develop), and has excellent safety profile. The treatment needs to be repeated after 7 days to kill any newly hatched lice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermethrin 1% lotion\u003C/strong\u003E is also effective but there are increasing reports of resistance. It works as an insecticide by disrupting nerve cell membranes in the lice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWet combing with conditioner\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective if done properly and consistently, but has only a 40% success rate even when performed daily. It is best used as an adjunct to other treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal head shaving\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as first-line treatment given the effectiveness and availability of other options, and the potential psychological impact, particularly in adolescents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ivermectin\u003C/strong\u003E should be reserved for cases that have failed topical therapy or where topical treatment is impractical. It requires prescription and carries a greater risk of side effects than topical treatments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The location of the nits (empty eggs) relative to the scalp can differentiate from current or previous infection.","Dimeticone 4% gel is an effective first-line treatment for head lice that works by physically blocking the lice\u0027s respiratory system.","Head lice resistance to permethrin is increasing, making non-insecticidal treatments preferable."],"references":["Frydenberg, A. (2003). Head Lice. Accessed from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/36d191bd-dc19-4e12-bcae-f8119a19a81e/attachment.aspx","Nolt D, Moore S, Yan AC, Melnick L; AAP Committee on Infectious Diseases, Committee on Practice and Ambulatory Medicine, Section on Dermatology. Head Lice. Pediatrics. 2022;150(4): e2022059282","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77327"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1561"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18586"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18586"},"attributes":{"mimeType":